Duck typing, on the other hand, is a concept in object-oriented programming that refers to the idea that an object's type is determined by the properties and methods it has, rather than by its class or inheritance. In other words, an object is considered to be of a certain type if it has the properties and methods that are expected of that type, regardless of its actual class or inheritance.

In TypeScript, duck typing is supported through the use of type assertions. A type assertion is a way to explicitly tell TypeScript that you know better than the type checker what the type of a variable or expression should be. For example, you might use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that a variable of type `any` should be treated as if it were of type `User`, even if it doesn't have all the properties and methods that are expected of a `User` object.

Here's an example of how you might use a type assertion in TypeScript to enable duck typing:
```
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

const user: User = { name: 'John', age: 30 };

function doSomethingWithUser(user: any) {
  console.log(user.name); // This will log "John"
  console.log(user.age); // This will log 30
}

doSomethingWithUser(user); // This will work, even though user is not a proper User object
```
In this example, the `user` variable is declared as an `any` type, which means that it can be any type of object. However, when we pass it to the `doSomethingWithUser` function, we use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that we know it should be treated as a `User` object. This allows us to access the `name` and `age` properties of the object, even though it doesn't have all the properties and methods that are expected of a `User` object.

Duck typing can be a useful technique in TypeScript when you have objects that don't fit neatly into a specific type, but have enough properties and methods to be useful in a particular context. However, it's important to use type assertions carefully and only when you are confident that the object you are working with has the properties and methods that you expect. Otherwise, you may end up with unexpected errors or bugs.

